reviewText: If you're a Pearl Jam fan, you need this DVD, period. If you're a casual Pearl Jam fan, you can see this DVD with fresh eyes and take in one extremely interesting take on one of the five best live bands in the last 40 years. This is an in depth look into my favorite band yes, but it also delivers some extremely memorable vignettes and performances that will more than satisfy the viewer. At first glance I thought the DVD was kind of short  since most Pearl Jam concerts don't go below 25 or 26 songs or 2 and a half hours of play. That being said, you need to know that this is a hybrid documentary, in depth look, concert film shot with great dedication, talent and love. If you've ever wanted to see a top view of the band during its performance, you're going to get it. if you've ever wanted to see how they determine a set list, you will see it and if you've ever wanted to watch a DVD dripping with energy and passion, this is your ticket to ride.The bonus extras are also quite a delicious nugget if you're a PJ fan having three things most fans look for. An Eddie solo. A collaboration with the opening band, in this case My Morning Jacket in an ultra solid version of a Who Classic, and one of their epic closers for good measure.Some people have mentioned different high lights for this DVD and I'm no different because when you're a fan of this band, it's a personal love you feel for certain songs. Mine were Alive, Porch, Come Back and Blood. I'd never seen Blood live before and seeing it on this DVD made my blood tingle since Eddie shreds his vocal chords most AC/DC like.From the vignettes I especially enjoyed Jeff's sessions and Boom Gaspar's clip. Lastly, the editing though a bit frantic works EXTREMELY well and you get to see all members showcase their talents and much to my delight, Jeff Ament's licks look as solid as ever since I think he's way underrated as a bassist and this DVD shows why he's a great one.In reality I could go on and on, but you'd be better to just buy this DVD. Trust me, if you like Pearl Jam... scratch that... if you like rock and roll, you should definitely include this DVD in your collection.

reviewText: As a guitar player, my only gripe is that McReady plays his strat on only a few of the tunes shown here... I swear to the maker he's just more of an animal when he straps that beat-up old instrument on.  But that aside, Vedder is and has been king of lead singers for the past decade or so: excellent stage presence with a humble and heartfelt demeanor and always a clever way of phrasing his thoughts... (as if people aren't aware of that by now).I'm very much a hard rock / screaming guitar fan, but Pearl Jam has grown on me over the years.  Despite that this is only the 2nd item of theirs I've purchased (the other being Ten, go figure).  What I like about this is it's for the most part songs that even casual fans will recognize, and for the most part they're all up tempo tunes, except for one or two, which happen to be among their most clutch and timeless numbers so are welcome additions even for casual fans.It's not one concert beginning to end, which sometimes is preferable, but the way they put it together, going from town to town and discussing more of what goes on behind the scenes: it's really an excellent DVD.  Hard core fans will simply love it because you're wanting all that stuff.  But as a casual fan, I can also say that aspect is not over the top: musically it absolutely rocks.
summary: A casual fan says... it ROCKS!
